newsitem.title: USA: CBOT soybeans close lower on wheat break, setback.
newsitem.headline: CBOT soybeans close lower on wheat break, setback.

text.p: CBOT soybean futures closed lower on a late break in wheat futures plus a short-term technical setback on signals the market was overbought, traders said.
"The wheat break weakened beans a little," said Ron Kucha of O'Connor and Co.
The wheat market rallied strongly Wednesday and was due for a setback amid signals the market was overbought and the soybean market also was viewed as short-term overbought.
Soybeans underwent a key technical reversal Wednesday and sagged slightly Thursday on profit taking.
Market sources said Wednesday's rally marked a key technical reversal in the January contract and suggested prices could climb above $7.14 per bushel in the next few weeks.
The session high for January was $7.12 per bushel which is where buying waned and the session low of $7.03 was set near the close.
Commercial buying was featured early in the session along with follow through from Wednesday's technical breakout.
Soybeans closed 3/4 to four cents per bushel lower, with January down one cent at $7.06.
